PL/php - PHP as a procedural language for PostgreSQL
====================================================

PL/php lets you write PostgreSQL functions in PHP.  Stored inside the database,
they can be used as plain functions, set-returning functions, and triggers,
with much of the power of a native PostgreSQL function plus the convenience of
PHP's standard library.

This is release 2.0, modernized for current software:

  * PostgreSQL 18 (also builds on PostgreSQL 16).
  * PHP 8 Zend API (tested with PHP 8.3), using the embed SAPI.
  * Installed the modern way, as an extension: CREATE EXTENSION plphp;
    (an untrusted, superuser-only language -- see the SECURITY NOTE below).

See INSTALL for build/install instructions and doc/plphp.md for the language
reference.  HISTORY lists what changed in each release.


Quick example
-------------

    CREATE EXTENSION plphp;

    CREATE FUNCTION hello(text) RETURNS text LANGUAGE plphp AS $$
        return "Hello, {$args[0]}!";
    $$;

    SELECT hello('world');   -- Hello, world!


Requirements
------------

  * PostgreSQL 16 or newer, with server development files (pg_config).
  * PHP 8.x built with the embed SAPI and *without* ZTS (thread safety).
    On Debian/Ubuntu: the php8.x-dev and libphp8.x-embed packages.

See INSTALL for details.


SECURITY NOTE
-------------

PL/php is an UNTRUSTED language.  On historical PHP the trusted variant relied
on PHP's "safe_mode" to sandbox user code, but safe_mode was removed in PHP 5.4,
so nothing sandboxes PHP today: a function can do anything the PostgreSQL
server's OS user can do (read files, open sockets, run shell commands, etc.).
For that reason the language is created without the TRUSTED attribute and only
superusers can create PL/php functions.  Do not grant that ability to roles you
would not trust with the server's operating-system account.
